<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12500</anchor> <rss>jms-004N.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-004N</addr>  <route>jms-004N.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Linear and thunkable inverses</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> be a deductive system, and let <tex>f : A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. Then both the type of (linear, thunkable) <link href="jms-004O.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004O" title="Inverses in a deductive system">inverses</link> of <tex>f</tex> is a proposition.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12501</anchor> <rss>jms-004U.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-004U</addr>  <route>jms-004U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses and invertibility in deductive systems</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Inverses to morphisms in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> need not be unique due to the general failure of associativity; therefore, we must be careful when speaking of “invertible maps” or “isomorphisms”. It happens that both linear and thunkable inverses <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">are unique</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12502</anchor> <rss>jms-004O.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12503</anchor> <rss>jms-004R.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12504</anchor> <rss>jms-004O.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12505</anchor> <rss>jms-004P.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004P</addr>  <route>jms-004P.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Downshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. A <em>downshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link> object <tex>\mathord { \Downarrow }  A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">thunkable</link> map <tex>\mathsf { wrap } _{ A }  : A \vdash \mathord { \Downarrow }  A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">necessarily unique and linear</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf { unwrap } _{ A }  :  \mathord { \Downarrow }  A \vdash  A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12506</anchor> <rss>jms-004U.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-004U</addr>  <route>jms-004U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses and invertibility in deductive systems</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Inverses to morphisms in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> need not be unique due to the general failure of associativity; therefore, we must be careful when speaking of “invertible maps” or “isomorphisms”. It happens that both linear and thunkable inverses <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">are unique</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12507</anchor> <rss>jms-004O.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12508</anchor> <rss>jms-004R.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12509</anchor> <rss>jms-004R.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>12510</anchor> <rss>jms-004M.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004M</addr>  <route>jms-004M.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Upshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. An <em>upshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link> object <tex>\mathord { \Uparrow }  A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">linear</link> map <tex>\mathsf { force } _{ A }  :  \mathord { \Uparrow }  A \vdash  A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">necessarily unique and thunkable</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf { delay } _{ A }  : A \vdash   \mathord { \Uparrow }  A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>